{\"video_title\": \"What is a Prompt?\", \"transcript\": \"вЂ‹So what does the word prompt actually mean? вЂ‹Now we talk a lot about prompt engineering and вЂ‹we're talking about interaction with large language models. вЂ‹And so let's dive into this word a little bit because I want to give you a sense вЂ‹of the depth of what a prompt can be. вЂ‹It's more than just a question that you're asking to the large language model. вЂ‹So to do this, I think it's helpful to go through a couple of prompts and вЂ‹actually interact with chat GPT to understand the concept of a prompt and вЂ‹sort of the the dimensions to a prompt. вЂ‹So I start off here by just asking chat GPT, what does the word prompt mean? вЂ‹And it comes up with some really helpful. вЂ‹I think information for us to use when we're talking about prompts. вЂ‹One, it says it's a verb to cause or вЂ‹encourage someone to do something to spur them to action. вЂ‹And as an example, the teacher's reminder about the upcoming exam prompted вЂ‹the students to start studying. вЂ‹So part of what a prompt is, вЂ‹it is a call to action to the large language model it is something that is вЂ‹getting the large language model to start generating output for вЂ‹us basically to start generating words that will form the basis of our output. вЂ‹And those words could take all kinds of different formats. вЂ‹It could be software, defining the instructions and a program. вЂ‹It could be the words that we need for that. вЂ‹It could be words in a poem, it could be words and many, вЂ‹many different types of things, we could do it as structured data that we need. вЂ‹All of these things are possible. вЂ‹But the key is the prompt is basically our way of getting вЂ‹the large language model to begin to provide some output for us. вЂ‹The second thing it says is it's an adjective, вЂ‹it's done without delay on time. вЂ‹And this is an important thing to think about with large language models is we're вЂ‹prompting them right now to do this. вЂ‹But this is also a useful point of discussion because it prompt doesn't вЂ‹necessarily depending on how you work with. вЂ‹Have to be something that happens right now. вЂ‹Prompts can have time associated with them. вЂ‹And now we have a little bit of an illusion of time and вЂ‹I'll talk about this later in the course. вЂ‹But when we give prompts to the large language model like chat GPT, the prompt вЂ‹could affect what's happening right now in my next statement that I give it or вЂ‹in the current statement or it could affect something in the future. вЂ‹And this is because of some of the conversational capabilities of these вЂ‹large language models. вЂ‹Now we're going to talk about prompts themselves as conversations later on. вЂ‹But for now, the way to think about it is a prompt doesn't just have to be something вЂ‹that's immediate. вЂ‹It can be, but it doesn't have to be. вЂ‹The next thing it says is a prompt can be a noun, a cue or вЂ‹reminder that helps someone remember what they were supposed to do or say. вЂ‹Now this is important because we can use prompts to remind the large вЂ‹language model of information or things that it needs to do. вЂ‹And so we may be asking it to do something now, вЂ‹we may be asking it something to do in the future. вЂ‹In which case, it needs to remember something. вЂ‹So we need to give it a reminder of what it's trying to do. вЂ‹We may need to go back and вЂ‹give it a history of the conversation of things that have happened, вЂ‹other things that will help it remember what it's trying to do. вЂ‹And then it can be in another noun, a message or screen that appears вЂ‹on a computer or electronic device asking the user for input. вЂ‹So this is kind of a helpful thing because we can prompt вЂ‹the large language model to produce things for us. вЂ‹But the large language model if we structure things correctly can actually вЂ‹elicit information from the user. вЂ‹So the large language model can ask questions to us. вЂ‹So prompt could both serve as as a call to action or вЂ‹to spur spurring the large language model to action. вЂ‹Or it can actually be an input, it can be asking us for input. вЂ‹So the last output from the large language model could have been a question for вЂ‹the human and basically we are then providing information back to it. вЂ‹So prompts have a lot of different dimensions to them. вЂ‹And if you actually look at the definition of prompt, in fact, вЂ‹the definition that chat GBT gives us, вЂ‹it gives us sort of that nuance to the capabilities of a prompt. вЂ‹Now, I've gone on a little bit here and I'm going to give you an example of this, вЂ‹this time aspect to a prompt because I think this helps to see the complexity and вЂ‹dimensionality of this, of concept. вЂ‹I'm going to say from now on when I ask a question, вЂ‹suggest a better version of my question and ask me if I would like to use it. вЂ‹So right here, I'm starting off by saying from now on, вЂ‹I'm attaching time to my prompt. вЂ‹So it's not just immediate and we get a response. вЂ‹Sure I can do that. вЂ‹However, I will start, I ask you the original question to the best of my вЂ‹ability and it goes on to try to reframe this original question, вЂ‹which wasn't what I necessarily needed. вЂ‹But then I say, what color is the sky? вЂ‹Now notice we're done, right? вЂ‹We asked the original prompt was back here. вЂ‹I said from now on when I ask a question and вЂ‹it immediately gave us a response because of that prompt. вЂ‹But now I'm going to ask a follow on question, but вЂ‹the earlier prompt is going to affect this question. вЂ‹So right now I'm asking it something immediate. вЂ‹What color is the sky? вЂ‹And it responds with a possible better version of the question could be. вЂ‹What is the scientific explanation for the blue color of the sky during the daytime? вЂ‹Would you like me to use this version instead? вЂ‹And then I say yes. вЂ‹Now notice here, we have a lot of those different dimensions of a prompt вЂ‹that we talked about. вЂ‹Up here we are creating a prompt that isn't just immediate, вЂ‹it is going to affect us in the future. вЂ‹It's going to continue to influence the output of the large language model. вЂ‹So it is we can have immediate prompts that right now, right at this moment, вЂ‹do something, but we can also have prompts that span time. вЂ‹And in this case, that's what we're doing. вЂ‹We're creating something from now on go and do this. вЂ‹Now, we're going to have an immediate prompt, which is what color is the sky? вЂ‹We're asking this right now and вЂ‹now our earlier prompt that we provided that was spanning time is now вЂ‹impacting the way that the large language model responds to our questions. вЂ‹So now what's happening is it's taking our current immediate question, вЂ‹what color is the sky? вЂ‹But it's using the context that we had previously said to suggest better versions вЂ‹of all of our questions. вЂ‹And then ask us if we'd like to use them to generate its output and its output is, вЂ‹here's a better question, what is the scientific explanation for вЂ‹the blue color of the sky during daytime? вЂ‹And you can see how that really is a better question than my first question. вЂ‹My first question was sort of vague, didn't provide enough context. вЂ‹And now it's giving us a more specific question that truly is better. вЂ‹And that's because of this prompt that we attached some time to it, вЂ‹we said from now on. вЂ‹And so it's influencing what's said. вЂ‹Now, the other thing that we can see is we talked about a prompt being something вЂ‹that can elicit information from the user. вЂ‹And so now we are seeing that the chat GBT in this case, вЂ‹the large language model is asking us for information. вЂ‹It's prompting us. вЂ‹It's soliciting information. вЂ‹And it's saying, would you like me to use this version of the question instead? вЂ‹So now we've got that extra dimension of a prompt. вЂ‹It's soliciting information from us and we say yes and then it goes and вЂ‹answers the question and it says great to answer your revised question. вЂ‹The blue color of the sky during the daytime is due to a phenomenon called вЂ‹raleigh scattering or ray scattering. вЂ‹And I apologize, I don't know this term and вЂ‹I'm actually learning something from Chat GBT as I read this. вЂ‹The earth's atmosphere is composed of various gasses and вЂ‹particles that scatter sunlight in all directions. вЂ‹Blue light has a shorter wavelength and higher frequency than other colors, вЂ‹which causes it to scatter more easily in the atmosphere. вЂ‹The results of this results in the blue color that we see when we look up at вЂ‹the sky on a clear day. вЂ‹Now, we've seen a lot of different dimensions to prompts through this short вЂ‹interaction. вЂ‹We've seen creating time prompts that span longer. вЂ‹We then see an immediate prompt that's spurring the large language model to вЂ‹action. вЂ‹We see the concept of the large language model, вЂ‹prompting and getting input from us. вЂ‹And then we see the output of all of this. вЂ‹Now, one of the things to note is we also talked about memory, вЂ‹that the prompt had a source of a concept of sort of memory to it. вЂ‹And we'll talk about how this works in the future. вЂ‹But right here I say from now on when I ask a question, that's something that вЂ‹the large language model has to remember in the future interactions. вЂ‹And we'll see how it actually does this. вЂ‹And so then when I say, what color is the sky, it's remembering that I said, вЂ‹whenever I ask a question, ask a better version of a question and вЂ‹then it's responding right here with the better version of the question. вЂ‹And then if I go and I do this again, we'll see that it still remembers my вЂ‹original statement that it needs to suggest better versions of my question. вЂ‹So I said, how many countries are there in the world? вЂ‹And it says a better version of your question would be, вЂ‹what is the current estimated number of countries in the world? вЂ‹And how is a country defined? вЂ‹Would you like me to use this version instead? вЂ‹And then I say yes and then says, great. вЂ‹As of my knowledge cut off in September 2021 there were 195 вЂ‹recognized sovereign states or countries in the world. вЂ‹However, this number may vary depending on how a country is defined. вЂ‹The United Nations, for example, has 193 member states. вЂ‹While other organizations and countries may recognize different numbers. вЂ‹Generally, a country is defined as a sovereign state with its own government, вЂ‹territory and international recognition. вЂ‹Now, one other interesting thing that we talked about is that вЂ‹a prompt has some memory associated with it. вЂ‹And this also shows us some of the limitations that the large вЂ‹language models, knowledge cuts off in September 2021. вЂ‹So one of the other things that we may need to do for вЂ‹the large language model is we may need to remind it вЂ‹of what has happened since it was finished being trained. вЂ‹And we'll see how it actually does this. вЂ‹And so then when I say, what color is the sky, it's remembering that I said, вЂ‹whenever I ask a question, ask a better version of a question and вЂ‹then it's responding right here with the better version of the question. вЂ‹And then if I go and I do this again, we'll see that it still remembers my вЂ‹original statement that it needs to suggest better versions of my question. вЂ‹So I said, how many countries are there in the world? вЂ‹And it says a better version of your question would be, вЂ‹what is the current estimated number of countries in the world? вЂ‹And how is a country defined? вЂ‹Would you like me to use this version instead? вЂ‹And then I say yes and then says, great. вЂ‹As of my knowledge cut off in September 2021 there were 195 вЂ‹recognized sovereign states or countries in the world. вЂ‹However, this number may vary depending on how a country is defined. вЂ‹The United Nations, for example, has 193 member states. вЂ‹While other organizations and countries may recognize different numbers. вЂ‹Generally, a country is defined as a sovereign state with its own government, вЂ‹territory and international recognition. вЂ‹Now, one other interesting thing that we talked about is that вЂ‹a prompt has some memory associated with it. вЂ‹And this also shows us some of the limitations that the large вЂ‹language models, knowledge cuts off in September 2021. вЂ‹So one of the other things that we may need to do for вЂ‹the large language model is we may need to remind it вЂ‹of what has happened since it was finished being trained. вЂ‹And we can use a prompt to provide information to the large language model вЂ‹like chat GPT about what happened after it was trained. вЂ‹So we can also use it to provide information that the large language model вЂ‹didn't have access to when it was trained like our own private information or вЂ‹other things. вЂ‹Now, of course, you have to be cognizant that when you're using chat GPT or вЂ‹many of these other tools, you're actually sending information to their servers. вЂ‹So you do want to make sure that that is something that you're willing to do before вЂ‹doing this. вЂ‹But if you're using a large language model locally on your machine or вЂ‹you're willing to send the information, you can provide information that it вЂ‹doesn't have access to in order to reason about. вЂ‹So a prompt can also be about providing information to one of these language вЂ‹models. вЂ‹So if we look at this example and вЂ‹we say what was Vanderbilt Universities acceptance вЂ‹rate in 2020 it should have access to that. вЂ‹And so it provides this information, it says the acceptance rate was 9.6%. вЂ‹If we say what was Vanderbilt University's acceptance rate in 2022? вЂ‹It will say I'm sorry, but вЂ‹it doesn't have access to that information because it was cut off in 2021. вЂ‹If we then provided that information. вЂ‹So here, I'm cutting and pasting the admissions data that was released and вЂ‹published by Vanderbilt just a few days ago. вЂ‹So it clearly didn't have access to this, but I now provide this to it in a prompt. вЂ‹Then it says based on the information you provided, вЂ‹it appears that Vanderbilt University's acceptance rate for вЂ‹the regular decision applicants for the class of 2026 was 4.7%. вЂ‹So a prompt can also serve as a way of providing new and вЂ‹updated information to the large language model like we saw in this example.\"}